AGI - The villages of Italy are certainly a cultural and economic treasure, also seen an impact of 5 billion euros per year on the national GDP, with about 9 million visitors (32% foreign) and 90 thousand employees, but at the same time they are characterized by a marked phenomenon of depopulation, much greater than the average of the Italian municipalities.
A data, this, also highlighted today in the study 'The economic and employment impact of tourism and the digitization in the most beautiful villages of Italy' presented in a meeting at the Istituto della Enciclopedia Italiana Treccani, in collaboration with the association "I Borghi più belli d'Italia", an association that since 2002 works to valorize the small towns that express an excellence of our Country and its beauty.
<div </div
&nbsp;
In particular, according to the Istat surveys, the Municipalities listed in the list of the "most beautiful villages in Italy" have an average population of approximately half of that of the Italian municipalities in the complex. In the period 2011-2021 there was an average reduction of the population living in the villages of -4,2%, in the face of a reduction of the resident population at national level equal to 0.7% in the same period. The forecast is that this phenomenon will be emphasized in the period 2020-2030, with a variation of -4.4% of population in the villages in front of an average reduction of the Italian municipalities of -2,8%. Thus, it is estimated that in 2030 the population living in the villages considered most beautiful in Italy will be about 1 million 285 thousand people against 1 million 344 thousand people registered in 2020.
A help could come from digitization and smart-working, considered possible relaunch levers of the villages. From the analysis conducted by Deloitte, it emerges that the historical evolution of the cover of the ultra-Larga band (BUL) in the most beautiful villages of Italy is growing in recent years, both considering the municipalities and the (UI) housing units covered: today 63.9% of the villages enjoy a cover 'Fiber to the Home' (FTTH), and is a very important percentage, if it is considered that only in 2019 this arrived just 2.2%. Only with such infrastructure development, in fact, will it be possible to reduce the market gap and create conditions of economic and social development on site for workers.
<div </div
&nbsp;
A very encouraging figure is then that of the growth of the number of workers who began to stay in the villages in smart-working mode following the Covid-19 pandemic. This phenomenon seems to confirm an ongoing trend. In fact, according to Inapp's research, 41.5% of workers would be willing to move to a more isolated place in contact with nature and 34.5% in a small town. This is a phenomenon to be observed in parallel to the average digitization level of enterprises, which in 2022 recorded a significant improvement. According to Istat data, companies with a "High" or "Very high" level of digitization, measured on the basis of the activities of a digital nature that enterprises are able to cover, have in fact reached approximately 32% in the North-West and 29% in the North-East. Instead, in the Centre and in the Mezzogiorno, the percentage, although rising, remains at a lower level (23%). &nbsp;
